For \( n \) not square-free, \( g(n) = 0 \). 4. **Applying to \( f(n) \)**: - Since \( f \) is the inverse of \( \text{id} \), we have \( f(n) = g(n) \). - Therefore, \( f(n) \) is non-zero only if \( n \) is square-free, and for square-free \( n \), \( f(n) = (-1)^k n \) where \( k \) is the number of distinct prime factors. 5. **Factorizing 2023**: - \( 2023 = 7 \times 17^2 \). - Since \( 2023 \) has a squared prime factor (17²), it is not square-free. 6. **Conclusion**: - For \( n \) not square-free, \( f(n) = 0 \). - Therefore, \( f(2023) = 0 \). \[ \boxed{0} \]
